# AI Policy

This provider's AI usage rules track two layers:

1. The Open Home Foundation **upstream policy** that governs
   `music-assistant/server` — the repository this provider (`{{ domain }}`)
   is eventually inlined into. Canonical text:
   [`music-assistant/.github/AI_POLICY.md`](https://github.com/music-assistant/.github/blob/main/AI_POLICY.md).
2. The **ecosystem policy** for `trudenboy/ma-provider-*` and
   `trudenboy/ma-provider-tools`, including how the upstream-boundary works.
   Canonical text:
   [`trudenboy/ma-provider-tools/AI_POLICY.md`](https://github.com/trudenboy/ma-provider-tools/blob/main/AI_POLICY.md).

Both documents are binding. When they disagree, **upstream wins** — because
this provider's code will land in `music-assistant/server`, where upstream
policy is the only one that applies.

## Local highlights

- AI assistants may write code, draft commit messages, and draft PR
  descriptions for work in this repo. A human contributor owns each PR and
  must be able to explain every change in their own words.
- Replies to human reviewers must be in the contributor's own words. Grammar
  and clarity help from AI is fine; substance is not.
- Replies to AI review comments (GitHub Copilot, code-scanning bots, etc.)
  may be AI-drafted, but the contributor must read and apply judgement
  before posting. Once a human joins the same thread, the previous rule
  applies to every reply after that point.
- No AI assistant may open, comment on, push to, or close anything in
  `music-assistant/*` directly. The only path is the
  `upstream-pr.yml.j2`-rendered workflow in `ma-provider-tools`, which
  opens the upstream PR as a draft with a human-attestation checklist that
  the contributor must check before requesting review.
- AI co-author trailers (`Co-Authored-By: Claude ...`) are welcome in this
  repo's commits as honest disclosure. They are stripped at the upstream
  boundary so they don't appear in `music-assistant/server` history.

